post_text:
Back to School Q & A

"Parents and community members, please take a moment to read the KUSD fact sheet. There seems to be a lot of inaccurate information on social media about schools opening indefinitely online or without any support. We are starting school on August 17. If we start virtually because our COVID numbers don't meet the criteria for opening in-person, we will still provide a place for your student to work in small groups if needed. Online is a choice pathway. KUSD will do everything possible to support our students and families."

- Superintendent Dr. Gretchen Dorner

https://www.kusd.org/2020/07/27/back-to-school-questions-and-answers/

REGISTRATION & ENROLLMENT INFORMATION

Have you enrolled your child yet?

The 2020-2021 school year is quickly approaching! Whether you are enrolling your student for the first time, or updating your child's registration information, be sure to head over to the KUSD website to begin the digital registration process:

https://www.kusd.org/community/registration/

Although KUSD #20 will be providing distance education options for the 2020-2021 school year (details here: https://www.kusd.org/community/online-learning/), please remember that all students must be enrolled with a KUSD school in order to be eligible for those programs.

post_text:
Kingman Unified School District's
Kindergarten Virtual Round-Up

On Thursday, May 21st, parents will be able to enroll their upcoming kindergarten student(s) digitally by going to the KUSD website. A link to the enrollment page will be provided closer to the enrollment day. So be sure to check back with our social media, and visit KUSD.org regularly for specific links and details!

Each school will also be providing welcome videos, hosted on our website, for you and your children to view. That way you get a chance to see, and be just a little more familiar with, your new school! Exciting, right?!

We look forward to meeting all the new students coming our way! See you on May 21st for the KUSD Kindergarten Virtual Round-Up!

post_text: Nearly 75 awesome parents & grandparents took time out of their busy day to visit their child's elective classes on Wednesday, January 29 during Kingman Middle School's first-ever Bobcat Parent Day! Families were able to experience the exciting activities in the school's Band, Choir, Culinary Arts, Physical Education, Technology & Visual Arts classes throughout the day. These co-curricular elective enCORE classes strive to develop well-rounded, highly achieving young adults. Bravo, Bobcat Families!

Families were able to experience the exciting activities in the school's Band, Choir, Culinary Arts, Physical Education, Technology & Visual Arts classes throughout the day. These co-curricular elective enCORE classes strive to develop well-rounded, highly achieving young adults. Bravo, Bobcat Families!

It may be the holiday season, but tax season is just around the corner! So get yourself a gift by giving a tax-credit donation to a school near you!

The tax credit program gets you a dollar-for-dollar credit on your taxes, and gives schools the ability to directly benefit students. Donations can be given towards clubs, sports, and many other extracurricular activities!

Check out our tax credit informational pamphlet for more information:
https://www.kusd.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/TaxCreditPamphletDec2019.pdf

Or fill out a donation form:
https://www.kusd.org/wp-content/uploads/pdfs/TaxCreditForm02.pdf

Band fans braved the cold Wednesday evening to cheer on Mohave County's award winning high school bands during the 10th annual Marching Exhibition!

Kingman High School's Bulldog, Lake Havasu High School's Knights, and Lee Williams High School's Volunteer Bands performed their half-time competitions shows for the crowd as the bands near the end of their marching season. A special appearance was made by the Kingman Middle School Band during the event's opening ceremonies.

Wish all three high school bands good luck as they compete this weekend in the Arizona Band & Orchestra Directors Association State Semi-Final Festival at Hamilton High School in Chandler!

Students simply cannot learn to their full potential unless their nutritional needs are met. That's why KUSD takes great care to provide lunch options full of healthy, enriching foods designed to encourage healthy minds!

Not only does KUSD meet all state and federal requirements, but the district is going above and beyond the healthy lunch call - by implementing a salad, fruit, and vegetable bar! KUSD plans to have these healthy food stations available soon for all schools.

Manzanita Elementary School students sure enjoy their healthy school lunches! Here are some pictures of KUSD Dragons feeding their bodies and their minds!

To read more about KUSD nutrition programs, or view school menus, you can visit our nutrition website at: http://district.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/kingmanusd/

post_text:
The Ellis Island Experience was hosted today at White Cliffs Middle School!

Students who participated were put in the shoes of an immigrant being proccessed through Ellis Island around the turn of the 20th century.

Students were funneled through an extensive network of stations which included:

- New Immigrant Arrival Line
- Baggage Claim
- Declarations and Documentation
- Physical Exam
- Medical, Vision and IQ Exam
- Quarantine
- Political Affiliation, Job Aptitude, and Personal Life Interview
- Currency Exchange & Train Ticket Purchase
- New Citizen Welcome Room (Popcorn and a Movie)

There were many waiting areas, long lines, and frustrating chances for paticipants to be sent backwards should anything go awry; simulating the difficult proccess our ancestors may have faced.

The experience was organized by "Team Spice," 8th grade educators of the school, and run by a group of volunteers.

(Video Music by bensound.com)

Students were funneled through an extensive network of stations which included:

- New Immigrant Arrival Line
- Baggage Claim
- Declarations and Documentation
- Physical Exam
- Medical, Vision and IQ Exam
- Quarantine
- Political Affiliation, Job Aptitude, and Personal Life Interview
- Currency Exchange & Train Ticket Purchase
- New Citizen Welcome Room (Popcorn and a Movie)

There were many waiting areas, long lines, and frustrating chances for paticipants to be sent backwards should anything go awry; simulating the difficult proccess our ancestors may have faced.

The experience was organized by "Team Spice," 8th grade educators of the school, and run by a group of volunteers.

(Video Music by bensound.com)

As we remember the events of 9/11, Kingman Unified School District is honored to be a part of a nation that stands unified and tall even in the face of adversity. We are proud to be educators that work to inspire our future generations while remembering and teaching the past.

Today, many schools throughout our district are honoring the memory of the twin tower attacks in a variety of ways. Manzanita Elementary School recognizes the day by having a free-dress day so that their students can wear red, white, and blue.

How do you recognize Patriot Day?
